  "opinion": "When I think about the gender gap in science, I remember watching my father work in the garage fixing cars and my mother teaching me to read at the kitchen table. Back in my day, science was a man’s world, but I never saw any girls in the lab coats. Now, as a retired woman from Washington DC, I’ve seen the world change. The gap isn’t just about numbers—it’s about who gets to dream big. I believe we should address it, but not with grand gestures. It starts with simple things: encouraging girls to ask questions, supporting them when they stumble, and making sure they feel they belong. In my time, we didn’t have the internet to show girls that they could be engineers or doctors. Now, with social media, we can share stories of young women in STEM fields. I volunteer at the local community center, and I’ve seen how a single conversation can spark a girl’s interest in science. The gap is real, but it’s fixable. We don’t need to overhaul the system overnight. Instead, we should focus on the small steps—like having more women mentors, creating safe spaces for girls to explore science, and letting them know that their curiosity is valuable. My children never had to deal with the same barriers I faced, and that’s a gift. So yes, we should address the gap, but in a way that respects the slow pace of change and the importance of individual stories.",
